  "text": "A side view of the velocity bulge phenomenon for test case W0-Q15 is illustrated in Fig. 4b . Two lateral velocity profiles in the wake of a cylinder (40 mm downstream of the cylinder centre) are plotted at two different heights: z=D ¼ 1:9 (where the maximum velocity bulge is observed) and at z=D ¼ 4:1 (corresponding to the constant-velocity region). The velocity bulge is clearly visible in the cylinder alignment (y = 260 mm) and is associated with a weaker wake at z=D ¼ 1:9 compared with the wake in the constantvelocity region. On the other hand, in the free stream region between two longitudinal rows of cylinders (280\\y\\320 mm), the velocity values at z=D ¼ 1:9 and z=D ¼ 4:1 are very similar (despite measurement scatter), indicating that the velocity bulge vanishes in this region. The velocity bulge phenomenon was first reported in the literature by Liu et al. [CITATION_1] and was reproduced in LES simulations conducted by Stoesser et al. [CITATION_2] . In common with our observations, Liu et al. [CITATION_3] found the velocity bulge to be clearly pronounced in line with a cylinder row and to disappear in the free stream region between two longitudinal rows of cylinders. However, unlike the present study, they measured the maximum bulge closer to the bed at z=D % 0:5. Liu et al. [CITATION_4] explain the velocity bulge by the horseshoe vortex at the foot of the cylinder; the legs of this vortex would transport fast fluid from the free stream region to the wake region. However, for a high bed roughness with a characteristic length of the same order of magnitude as the cylinder diameter, we may ponder whether a horseshoe vortex can in fact develop and whether its formation is not hindered by bedinduced turbulent motion. Figure 5 illustrates the ADV-time series of lateral velocity for test case W0-Q15 at distances of 4 cm upstream of a cylinder (Point C, Fig. 5a ) and of 4 cm downstream of a cylinder (Point A, Fig. 5b ) as well as at four different elevations. Lateral velocity is a good indicator of the presence of periodic coherent structures associated with the von Kármán vortex street. The bed is smooth so the ADV probe measurements in test case W0-Q15 are of good quality even close to the bed. Downstream of the cylinder, clear periodic oscillations of almost constant amplitude can be observed in the constant-velocity region (z=D ¼ 4:1 and 10.1 in Fig. 5b ). These periodic oscillations are dampened, when moving downstream, and become less regular, but they are still visible 4 cm upstream of the next cylinder (z=D ¼ 4:1 and 10.1 in Fig. 5a ). These oscillations are less and less coherent, when moving downwards, until they almost vanish close to the bed (z=D ¼ 1:0), where random fluctuations of bed-induced turbulence can be observed (z=D ¼ 1:0 in Fig. 5a, b) . This analysis infers that the von Kármán vortex street is well developed in the constantvelocity region and is associated with large, high energy vortices, whereas in the boundary layer, the vortex street is unstructured probably by bed-induced turbulence. The drag and energy loss in the cylinder wake are reduced due to the absence of large vortices, which would explain the velocity bulge.",
